An extra layer to this topic btw, is that internet algorithms also prioritise controversial or sensationalist content over educational and factual content, because it tends to get more clicks. The whole clickbait thing. This heavily weights the balance in favour of fringe beliefs even more. It is an issue with TV and Newspapers too, with the news media putting sensationalist stories at the forefront for ratings. But the problem has only gotten worse with the internet, where anyone can say anything without any accountability, and lies spread like wildfire (hence why people were already on edge about covid misinformation before Joe Rogan started to contribute to it.) So this is another reason why people are calling for more accountability from companies like Spotify (and social media in general) to adjust algorithms such that they don't only favour what is sensationalist (and therefore profitable) but also are responsible platforms that try to push educational content, not just controversy that further divides our society and fractures our unity (to where we can't even agree on basic universal truths anymore.)

Your idea of free speech is to compel an artist to remain an associate of a business that they no longer wish to do business with? Maybe you should understand free speech before you lecture others on it. Understand statecraft, because Spotify is not the State.

Do you not even understand the basic concept of "the marketplace of ideas"? You put forth your ideas, you say your piece. But that is not where it ends. Then the mechanism by which this MARKETPLACE works... is that then people have THEIR say in response, in order to filter the good ideas from the bad, leading to social progress. In a marketplace, not every product has equal success. The marketplace does not mean all words are equal. It means that concepts that ring true will be perpetuated, while bad concepts will sink to the fringes where they belong. If you don't want fringe ideas like racism to become mainstream, then you engage with the marketplace in that manner, by refusing to do business with companies that push fringe, harmful concepts (and underpay you to boot.)
